Bolivian Fertilizer Plant

Getting over the development hurdle

Travis McArthur

Review & Model

  • Recall that our objective is to determine the circumstances under which the fertilizer plant is a "good idea"

  • My model is based on Ciccone & Matsuyama (1996)

  • Emphasizes "vertical complementarity" between intermediate and final goods industries

  • Contrast with horizontal complementarity of Rosenstein-Rodan (1943)

Final Good

  • One homogenous consumption good (food)
  • Production function:
  • \[C=F(X,H)=\underset{X_{1},X_{2},H_{1},H_{2}\geq0}{\max}\left\{ X_{1}^{\alpha}H_{1}^{1-\alpha}+X_{1}^{1-\alpha}H_{1}^{\alpha}\mid X_{1}+X_{2}\leq X,H_{1}+H_{2}\leq H\right\}\]
  • X is a composite intermediate good. H is labor. \(\alpha \in (0,0.5)\)
  • \(P=\) Price of X
  • \(w=\) Price of H
  • \[P>w \implies F(X,H)=X_{1}^{\alpha}H_{1}^{1-\alpha}\]
  • \[P < w\implies F(X,H)=X_{1}^{1-\alpha}H_{1}^{\alpha}\]

Low use of intermediate inputs

Intermediate good \(X\)

  • \(X_{t}\) is a composite of differentiated inputs \(x_{t}(i)\) at time \(t\). CES form:

\[X_{t}=\left[\underset{0}{\overset{n_{t}}{\int}}\left[x_{t}(i)\right]^{1-1/\sigma}di\right]^{\sigma/(\sigma-1)}\]

  • But we need discrete inputs:

  • \[X_{t}=\left[\underset{i=1}{\overset{n_{t}}{\sum}}\left[x_{t}(i)\right]^{1-1/\sigma}\right]^{\sigma/(\sigma-1)}\]

  • \(n_{t}\) is the number of intermediate inputs available in the marketplace at time \(t\).

  • \(\sigma\) is the direct partial elasticity of substitution between every pair of products. We restrict \(\sigma > 1\).

  • Hence higher \(n_{t}\) implies greater TFP for final good.

Price of intermediates is decreasing in \(n_{t}\)

  • \(P_{t}=n_{t}^{1/(1-\sigma)}w_{t}\)

Hence: \[n_{t} < 1 \implies w_{t} < P_{t}\] \[n_{t} > 1 \implies w_{t} > P_{t}\]

Evolution of the economy in \(n_{t}-V_{t}\) space

  • If the elasticity of substitution between \(X\) and \(H\) in the final goods production is less than \(\sigma\) for all \(P_{t}/w_{t}\), then the steady state is guaranteed to be unique.
  • Let \(V_{t}=v_{t}/C_{t}\), where \(v_{t}\) is the value of ownership an intermediate goods firm (present discounted value of profits) and \(C_{t}\) is final goods production in time \(t\).

What are conditions for multiple steady states?

With the dual technology production function, elasticity of substitution between \(X\) and \(H\) is \(\infty\) when \(n_{t}=1\) (and 1 when \(n_{t} \neq 1\)). Does this guarantee more than one steady state? No. 

## sigma = 6 , alpha = 0.17

We additionally need:

\[\dfrac{\sigma}{1-\sigma}-1<\dfrac{L}{\rho\cdot a_{n}}<\dfrac{\sigma-\alpha}{1-\alpha}\]

Where \(\rho\) is the temporal discount rate (let's say \(\rho=0.95\)), \(L\) is the total labor force in the economy, and \(a_{n}\) is the labor unit cost of starting up a new firm that produces a new intermediate input variety.

## sigma = 7.6 , alpha = 0.33 , L/a= 15
